eanup of Contaminated Sites.\" Report from a roundtable held in Washington, DC, June 28, 2002, [http://www.cpeo.org/ cpeo.org],  accessed December 19, 2005.\n* Case, Bridgette Dawn. \"The women's protective union: Union women activists in a union town, 1890-1929\" (PhD Dissertation. Montana State University-Bozeman,  2004) [http://scholarworks.montana.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1/1049/CaseB1204.pdf?sequence=1 online]\n*Curran, Mary E. 1996. \"The Contested Terrain of Butte, Montana: Social Landscapes of Risk and Resiliency.\" Master's thesis, University of Montana.\n*LeCain, Timothy. 1998. \"Moving Mountains: Technology and Environment in Western Copper Mining.\" PhD Dissertation, University of Delaware.\n*Quivik, Frederic. 1998. \"Smoke and Tailings: An Environmental History of Copper Smelting Technologies in Montana, 1880\u20131930.\" PhD Dissertation, University of Pennsylvania.\n\n===Other===\n*Mercier, Laurie. 2001. ''Anaconda: Labor, Community, and Culture in Montana's Smelter City'' (University of Illinois Press).\n*{{cite book|last=Parrett|first=Aaron|title=Literary Butte: A History in Novels & Film|publisher=The History Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1-626-19836-4}}\n*St. Clair, Jeffrey. 2003. \"Something About Butte.\" ''Counterpunch, an online magazine'' www.counterpunch.org, accessed October 3, 2005.\n*Toole, K. Ross. 1954. \"A History of the Anaconda Copper Mining Company: A Study in the Relationships between a State and its People and a Corporation, 1880\u20131950.\" PhD Dissertation, University of California-Los Angeles.\n\n===Primary sources===\n*[http://www.worldcatlibraries.org/search?q=Copper+camp%3A+stories+of+the+world%27s+greatest+mining+town&qt=owc_search Copper Camp: Stories of the world's greatest mining town, Butte, Montana]</u> compiled by Workers of the Writers' Program of the Work Projects Administration in the State of Montana.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Butte, Montana}}\n{{Wikisource1911Enc|Butte (Montana)}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Butte}}\n'''Local resources'''\n*[http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us City and County of ''Butte-Silver Bow'']\n*[https://scholarworks.umt.edu/butte_oralhistory/ Butte Oral History Project] (University of Montana Archives)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090805073649/http://www.buttecvb.com/ Butte Visitors Bureau]\n*[http://www.mtstandard.com/ The Montana Standard, the local newspaper]\n*[http://www.buttectec.org/ Butte Citizens Environmental Committee (CTEC), a Superfund Technical Assistance group]\n*[http://www.butteamericaradio.org/ KBMF, community radio station]\n\n'''Photographs and media'''\n*{{Commons category-inline|mining in Butte, Montana}}\n*[https://www.loc.gov/resource/g4254b.pm020527/ Panoramic (zoomable) view of Butte, Montana, 1904], via [[Library of Congress]] \n*[http://watch.montanapbs.org/video/1430375505 Hidden Fire: The Great Butte Explosion] Documentary produced by ''[[Montana PBS]]''\n\n{{Silver Bow County, Montana}}\n{{Montana}}\n{{Montana Regions and Towns with Breweries}}\n\n{{Coord|46|0|23|N|112|31|47|W|region:US-MT_type:city(34000)|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Butte, Montana]]\n[[Category:Cities in Montana]]\n[[Category:Cities in Silver Bow County, Montana]]\n[[Category:Irish-American neighborhoods]]\n[[Category:County seats in Montana]]\n[[Category:Census balances in the United States]]\n[[Category:Mining communities in Montana]]\n[[Category:Consolidated city-counties in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Consolidated city-county in Montana, United States}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Butte-Silver Bow\n| name                            = Butte\n| settlement_type                 = [[Consolidated city-county]]\n| nickname                        = Butte America\n| motto                           = The Richest Hill on Earth\n\n<!-- Images -->| image_skyline                   = Butte, Montana collage.png\n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = {{small|Clockwise, left to right: View of uptown Butte from west; [[Our Lady of the Rockies]]; Curtis Music Hall; aerial view of the [[Berkeley Pit]]; mine framehead; and the Finlen Hotel.}}\n| image_flag                      = [[File:Flag of Butte.png|150px|Flag of Butte]]\n| image_seal                      = Seal of Butte, Montana.png\n\n<!-- Maps -->| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = Location of Butte in Montana\n| image_map1                      = Silver Bow County Montana Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Butte Highlighted.svg\n| mapsize1                        = 250px\n| map_caption1                    = Map of Silver Bow County showing the city of Butte\n\n<!-- Location -->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = United States\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Montana]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of counties in Montana|County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Silver Bow County, Montana|Silver Bow]]\n\n<!-- Government -->| government_footnotes            = \n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| established_title               = [[Human settlement|Settled]]\n| established_date                = 1864\n\n<!-- Area -->| unit_pref                       = Imperial\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name =censusfacts/>\n| area_magnitude                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_land_km2                   = \n| area_water_km2                  = \n| area_total_sq_mi                = 716.82\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 716.25\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 0.57\n\n<!-- Population -->| population_as_of                = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_est                  = 34,284\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2018\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name =\"2010census\"/>\n| population_total                = 33,525\n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_density_sq_mi        = 46.8\n| population_metro                = <!-- General information -->\n| timezone                        = [[Mountain Time Zone|MST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22127\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Mountain Daylight Time|MDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22126\n| elevation_footnotes             = <ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65jET5cdV?url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/|archive-date=February 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| elevation_m                     = 1688\n| elevation_ft                    = 5538\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|45|59|56|N|112|31|27|W|region:US-MT|display=inline}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code                     = 59701, 59702, 59703, 59707, 59750\n| area_code                       = [[Area code 406|406]]\n| blank_name                      = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info                      = 30-11397\n| blank1_name                     = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n| blank1_info                     = 2409651<ref name=\"GR3\" />\n| website                         = http://co.silverbow.mt.us\n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''Butte''' is the [[county seat]] of [[Silver Bow County, Montana|Silver Bow County]], [[Montana]], United States. In 1977, the city and county governments consolidated to form the sole entity of Butte-Silver Bow. The city covers {{convert|718|mi2|0}}, and, according to the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], has a population of 33,503, making it Montana's fifth largest city. It is served by [[Bert Mooney Airport]] with airport code BTM.\n\nEstablished in 1864 as a [[mining camp]] in the northern [[Rocky Mountains]] on the [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]], Butte experienced rapid development in the late-nineteenth century, and was Montana's first major industrial city.<ref name=historyculture/> In its heyday between the late-nineteenth and early-twentieth centuries, it was one of the largest copper [[boomtown]]s in the [[American West]]. Employment opportunities in the mines attracted surges of Asian and European immigrants, particularly the [[Irish people|Irish]]; as of 2017, Butte has the largest population of [[Irish Americans]] per capita of any city in the United States.<ref name=irish/>\n\nButte was also the site of various historical events involving its mining industry and active [[trade union|labor union]]s and [[Socialism|Socialist]] politics, the most famous of which was the [[Butte, Montana labor riots of 1914|labor riot of 1914]]. Despite the dominance of the [[Anaconda Copper|Anaconda Copper Mining Company]], Butte was never a [[company town]]. Other major events in the city's history include the [[Speculator Mine disaster|1917 Speculator Mine disaster]], the largest hard rock mining disaster in world history.\n\nOver the course of its history, Butte's mining and [[smelting]] operations generated an excess of $48 billion worth of [[ore]], but also resulted in numerous environmental implications for the city: The upper [[Clark Fork River]], with headwaters at Butte, is the largest [[List of Superfund sites|Superfund site]] in the United States, and the city is also home to the [[Berkeley Pit]]. In the late-twentieth century, cleanup efforts from the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] were instated, and the [[Butte Citizens Technical Environmental Committee]] was established in 1984. In the 21st century, efforts at interpreting and preserving Butte's heritage are addressing both the town's historical significance and the continuing importance of mining to its economy and culture. The city's Uptown Historic District, on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], is one of the largest [[National Historic Landmark|National Historic Landmark Districts]] in the United States, containing nearly 6,000 contributing properties.<ref name=nrhp/> The city is also home to [[Montana Tech of the University of Montana|Montana Tech]], a public engineering and technical university.\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Butte, Montana}}\n\n===Early history and immigrants===\nPrior to Butte's formal establishment in 1864, the area consisted of a mining camp that had developed in the early 1860s.{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=70}} The city is located in the Silver Bow Creek Valley (or Summit Valley), a natural bowl sitting high in the Rockies straddling the [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]],{{sfn|Malone|2006|pages=3\u20134}} positioned on the southwestern side of a large mass of [[granite]] known as the [[Boulder Batholith]], which dates to the [[Cretaceous]] era.<ref name=deq/> In 1874, William L. Farlin founded the Asteroid Mine (subsequently known as the Travona); Farlin's founding of the Asteroid Mine attracted a significant number of prospectors seeking [[gold]] and [[silver]].<ref name=deq>{{cite web|url=http://deq.mt.gov/Land/AbandonedMines/linkdocs/183tech|work=Montana Department of Environmental Quality|title=Abandoned Mines: Historic Context|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101193351/http://deq.mt.gov/Land/AbandonedMines/linkdocs/183tech|archive-date=November 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The mines attracted workers from [[Cornwall]] (England), <ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=npQ6Hd3G4kgC|title=Harvard Encyclopedia of American Ethnic Groups|author=Thernstrom, Stephan|year=1980|p=243|publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University|isbn=978-0-674-37512-3|access-date=October 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704170128/http://books.google.com/books?id=npQ6Hd3G4kgC|archive-date=July 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Ireland, Wales, Lebanon, Canada, Finland, Austria, Italy, China, [[Montenegro]], Mexico, and more.<ref name=irisham>{{cite web|work=Irish America|title=Butte: Montana's Irish Mining Town|date=August 2010|author=Rota, Kara|url=http://irishamerica.com/2010/08/montanas-mining-town/|accessdate=November 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107030541/http://irishamerica.com/2010/08/montanas-mining-town/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In the ethnic neighborhoods, young men formed gangs to protect their territory and socialize into adult life, including the Irish of Dublin Gulch, the Eastern Europeans of the McQueen Addition, and the Italians of Meaderville.<ref>{{cite book|author=Finn, Janet L.|title=Mining Childhood: Growing Up in Butte, 1900-1960|year=2012|publisher=Montana Historical Society Press|isbn= 978-0-980-12925-0}}</ref>\n[[File:Butte Montana (15667252674).jpg|thumb|right|Butte courthouse and additional buildings, 1885]]\n\nAmong the migrants, many Chinese workers moved in, and amongst them set up businesses that led to the creation of a Chinatown in Butte. The Chinese migrations stopped in 1882 with the passage of the [[Chinese Exclusion Act]]. There was anti-Chinese sentiment in the 1870s and onwards due to racism on the part of the white settlers, exacerbated by economic depression, and in 1895, the chamber of commerce and labor unions started a boycott of Chinese owned businesses. The business owners fought back by suing the unions and winning. The history of the Chinese migrants in Butte is documented in the [[Mai Wah Museum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://visitmt.com/history/Montana_the_Magazine_of_Western_History/spring_summer04/buttechinatown.htm|title=Remembering Butte's Chinatown|author=Carrie Schneider|publisher=Official State of Montana Travel Information Site|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315155041/http://visitmt.com/history/Montana_the_Magazine_of_Western_History/spring_summer04/buttechinatown.htm|archivedate=March 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Lee, Rose Hum | year = 1948 | title = Social Institutions of a Rocky Mountain Chinatown | journal = Social Forces | volume = 27 | issue = 1 | pages = 1\u201311 | doi = 10.2307/2572452| jstor = 2572452 | author-link = Rose Hum Lee }}</ref>\n\nThe influx of miners gave Butte a reputation as a wide-open town where any vice was obtainable. The city's saloon and red-light district, called the \"Line\" or \"The Copper Block\", was centered on Mercury Street, where the elegant [[bordello]]s included the famous [[Dumas Brothel]].<ref name=baumler/> Behind the brothel was the equally famous [[Venus Alley]], where women plied their trade in small cubicles called \"cribs.\"<ref name=baumler/> The red-light district brought miners and other men from all over the region and remained open until 1982 after the closure of the Dumas Brothel; the city's red-light was one of the last such urban districts in the United States.<ref name=baumler>{{cite web|work=Montana Women's History Project|url=http://montanawomenshistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/ButteWalkingTour12_2013_Rev.pdf|title=Butte's Red Light District: A Walking Tour|author=Baumler, Ellen|publisher=Montana Historical Society|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017033017/http://montanawomenshistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/ButteWalkingTour12_2013_Rev.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Commercial breweries first opened in Butte in the 1870s, and were a large staple of the city's early economy; they were usually run by German immigrants, including Leopold Schmidt, Henry Mueller, and Henry Muntzer. The breweries were always staffed by union workers. Most ethnic groups in Butte, from Germans and Irish to Italians and various Eastern Europeans, including children, enjoyed the locally brewed lagers, bocks, and other types of beer.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Lozar, Steve|title=1,000,000 Glasses a Day: Butte's Beer History on Tap|journal=Montana|date=December 2006|volume=56|issue=4|pages=46\u201356}}</ref>\n\n===Industrial expansion===\n[[File:ANSELMO HEADFRAME AND TIPPLE LOOKING EAST - Butte Mineyards, Anselmo Mine, Butte, Silver Bow County, MT HAER MONT,47-BUT.V,1-A-32.tif|thumb|right|The Anselmo Mine, one of many in Butte, opened in 1887]]\nIn the late nineteenth century, copper was in great demand because of new technologies such as electric power that required the use of copper. Four industrial magnates fought for control of Butte's mining wealth. These four \"[[Copper Kings]]\" were [[William Andrews Clark|William A. Clark]],<ref>{{cite web|work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C000454|accessdate=October 28, 2017|title=CLARK, William Andrews, (1839 - 1925)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065500/http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C000454|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Marcus Daly]], [[F. Augustus Heinze]],<ref name=deq/> and James A. Murray.<ref>{{Cite book|title=James A. Murray : Butte's Radical Irish millionaire|last=1959-|first=Farley, Bill|isbn=978-0-878-42682-9|location=Missoula, Montana|oclc=1019743586|date = March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Anaconda Copper Mining Company began in 1881 when [[Marcus Daly]] bought a small mine named the Anaconda.  He was a part-owner, mine manager and engineer of the Alice, a silver mine in Walkerville, a suburb of Butte. While working in the Alice, he noticed significant quantities of high grade copper ore. Daly obtained permission to inspect nearby workings. After Daly's employers, the Walker Brothers, refused to buy the Anaconda, Daly sold his interest in the Alice and bought it himself. Daly asked [[George Hearst]], San Francisco mining magnate, for additional support. Hearst agreed to buy one-fourth of the new company's stock without visiting the site. While mining the silver left in his mine, huge deposits of [[copper]] were soon developed and Daly became a copper magnate. When surrounding silver mines \"played out\" and closed, Daly quietly bought up the neighboring mines, forming a mining company. Daly built a smelter at [[Anaconda, Montana]] (a company town) and connected his smelter to Butte by a railway. Anaconda Company eventually owned all the mines on Butte Hill.<ref>Laurie Mercier, ''Anaconda: Labor, Community, and Culture in Montana's Smelter City'' (University of Illinois Press, 2001)</ref>\n\nBetween 1884 and 1888, W.A. Clark constructed the [[Copper King Mansion]] in Butte, which became his second residence from his home in [[New York City]].{{sfn|Gordon|2015|pages=38\u201341}} He also, in 1899, purchased the [[Columbia Gardens (amusement park)|Columbia Gardens]], a small park which he developed into a full [[amusement park]], featuring a pavilion, [[rollercoaster]], and a lake for swimming and canoeing. Clark's expansion of the park was intended to \"provide a place where children and families could get away from the polluted air of the Butte mining industry.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Montana Standard]]|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/columbia-gardens-butte-s-lost-amusement-park/collection_a4b37cae-a30a-5806-a427-cebac2569a28.html|title=Columbia Gardens: Butte's lost amusement park|date=June 10, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045354/http://mtstandard.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/columbia-gardens-butte-s-lost-amusement-park/collection_a4b37cae-a30a-5806-a427-cebac2569a28.html|archive-date=September 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The city's rapid expansion was noted in an 1889 frontier survey: \"Butte, Montana, fifteen years ago a small placer-mining village clinging to the mountain side, has now risen to the rank of the first mining camp of the world... [It] is now the most populous city of Montana, numbering twenty-five thousand active, enterprising, prosperous inhabitants.\"<ref name=great>{{cite book|title=The Great Reservation|pages=39\u201340|year=1898 |location=Chicago |publisher=Poole Brothers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QVdNAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> In 1888 alone, mining operations in Butte had generated an \"almost inconceivable\" output of $23 million ({{Inflation|US|23000000|1888|fmt=eq}}) worth of ore.<ref name=great/>\n[[File:Columbia Gardens, Butte, Montana 1905.jpg|thumb|left|[[Columbia Gardens (amusement park)|Columbia Gardens]], an amusement park in Butte, {{circa}} 1905]]\n\nAround the turn of the twentieth century, prosperous mining had generated considerable wealth in Butte, and at the time was the largest city between [[Chicago]] and [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsmax.com/FastFeatures/biggest-cities-montana-population/2015/04/13/id/638229/|work=Newsmax|title=10 Biggest Cities in Montana|author=Lee, Don|date=April 13, 2015|accessdate=August 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822094013/http://www.newsmax.com/FastFeatures/biggest-cities-montana-population/2015/04/13/id/638229/|archive-date=August 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Copper ore mined from the Butte mining district in 1910 alone totaled {{convert|284000000|lb|kg}}; at the time, Butte was the largest producer of copper in North America and rivaled in worldwide metal production only by [[South Africa]].<ref name=deq/> The same year, an excess of {{convert|10000000|oz|kg}} of [[silver]] and {{convert|37000|oz|kg}} of [[gold]] were also discovered.<ref name=deq/> The amount of ore produced in the city earned it the nickname \"The Richest Hill on Earth.\"<ref name=deq/> With its large workforce of miners performing in physically dangerous conditions, Butte was the site of active [[labor union]] movements, and came to be known as \"the Gibraltar of Unionism.\"<ref name=union>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/lifestyles/unionism-in-butte-mines-contributes-to-city-s-fascinating-history/article_2877a26a-2720-5485-a4ab-e01f5106f14d.html|title=Unionism in Butte mines contributes to city's fascinating history|date=March 1, 2015|author=Bossard, Floyd|access-date=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107025914/http://mtstandard.com/lifestyles/unionism-in-butte-mines-contributes-to-city-s-fascinating-history/article_2877a26a-2720-5485-a4ab-e01f5106f14d.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=munday/>\n\nBy 1885, there were about 1,800 dues-paying members of a general union in Butte. That year the union reorganized as the [[Butte Miners' Union]] (BMU), spinning off all non-miners to separate [[craft unionism|craft unions]]. Some of these joined the [[Knights of Labor]], and by 1886 the separate organizations came together to form the Silver Bow Trades and Labor Assembly, with 34 separate unions representing nearly all of the 6,000 workers around Butte.{{sfn|Malone|2006|pages=76\u20137}} The BMU established branch unions in mining towns like Barker, Castle, Champion, Granite, and Neihart, and extended support to other mining camps hundreds of miles away. In 1892 there was [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho labor strike of 1892|a violent strike]] in [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]].{{sfn|Carlson|1984|p=50}} Although the BMU was experiencing relatively friendly relations with local management, the events in Idaho were disturbing. The BMU not only sent thousands of dollars to support the Idaho miners, they mortgaged their buildings to send more.{{sfn|Malone|2006|p=77}}\n\nThere was a growing concern that local unions were vulnerable to the power of [[Mine Owners' Association]]s like the one in Coeur d'Alene.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Overland Monthly|title=The Coeur d'Alene Riots, 1892|p=32|publisher=Samuel Carson|year=1895|via=Google Books|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UMARAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA32&dq=butte+montana+coeur+d%27alene+miners+association#v=onepage&q=butte%20montana%20coeur%20d'alene%20miners%20association&f=false}} {{free access}}</ref> In May 1893, about forty delegates from northern hard-rock mining camps met in Butte and established the [[Western Federation of Miners]] (WFM), which sought to organize miners throughout the West.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rayback, Joseph G.|title=A History of American Labor|year=2008|orig-year=1966|p=233|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-439-11899-3}}</ref> The Butte Miners' Union became Local Number One of the new WFM.{{sfn|Malone|2006|p=79}} The WFM [[Cripple Creek miners' strike of 1894|won a strike]] in [[Cripple Creek, Colorado]], the following year, but then in 1896\u201397 [[Leadville Colorado, Miners' Strike|lost another violent strike]] in [[Leadville, Colorado]], prompting the Montana State Trades and Labor Council to issue [[November 1897 proclamation|a proclamation to organize a new Western labor federation]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Philpott, William Philpott|title= The Lessons of Leadville|publisher=Colorado Historical Society|year=1995|p= 71|isbn=}}</ref> along [[Industrial unionism|industrial lines]].<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Colorado's Role in the American Labor Struggle: Western Unionism and the Labor Question 1894-1914|p=55|publisher=University of Colorado, Boulder|author=Rasmussen, Ryan|date=Fall 2013|url=https://scholar.colorado.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1750&context=honr_theses|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425115638/https://scholar.colorado.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1750&context=honr_theses|archivedate=April 25, 2018|url-status=dead}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Anaconda Copper and civil unrest===\n{{See also|Anaconda Copper|Speculator Mine disaster|Anaconda Road massacre}}\n[[File:IWW organizer Frank Little, c. 1917.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|[[Frank Little (unionist)|Frank Little]], an [[Industrial Workers of the World|IWW]] organizer who was lynched in Butte in 1917]]\nIn 1899, Daly joined with [[William Rockefeller]], [[Henry H. Rogers]], and [[Thomas W. Lawson (businessman)|Thomas W. Lawson]] to organize the Amalgamated Copper Mining Company.{{sfn|Malone|2006|p=137}} Not long after, the company changed its name to [[Anaconda Copper Mining Company]] (ACM). Over the years, Anaconda was owned by assorted larger corporations. In the 1920s, it had a virtual monopoly over the mines in and around Butte.{{sfn|Smith|2008|p=25}} Between approximately 1900 and 1917, Butte also had a strong streak of [[socialism|Socialist]] politics, even electing Mayor Lewis Duncan on the Socialist ticket in 1911, and again in 1913; Duncan was impeached in 1914 for neglecting duties after a bombing in the city's miners' hall in 1914.{{sfn|Calvert|1988|pages=43\u20137}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Lewis J. Duncan, Butte's Socialist mayor|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/lewis-j-duncan-butte-s-socialist-mayor/article_77f3176c-126d-520a-aa0b-4a70d50604db.html|work=The Montana Standard|author=Christensen, Kelly|date=October 12, 2014|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428181121/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/lewis-j-duncan-butte-s-socialist-mayor/article_77f3176c-126d-520a-aa0b-4a70d50604db.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt had also established itself as \"one of the most solid union cities in America.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Dubovsky, Melvyn|title=We Shall Be All: A History of the Industrial Workers of the World|year=2000|p=173|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn= 978-0-252-06905-5}}</ref> After 1905, Butte became a hotbed of [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW, or the \"Wobblies\") organizing.{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=73}} Rivalry between IWW supporters and the WFM locals culminated in the [[Butte, Montana labor riots of 1914]], and resulted in the loss of union recognition by the mine owners.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|p=125}} After the dissolution of the Miners' Union, the Anaconda Company attempted to inaugurate programs aimed at enticing employees.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|p=125}} However, a number of clashes between laborers, labor organizers, and the Anaconda Company ensued, including the 1917 lynching of IWW executive board officer [[Frank Little (unionist)|Frank Little]].{{sfn|Murphy|1997|p=224}} In 1920, company mine guards gunned down strikers in the [[Anaconda Road Massacre]].{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=33}} Seventeen were shot in the back as they tried to flee, and one man died.{{sfn|Murphy|1997|p=33}}\n\nSparked by a tragic accident more than {{convert|2000|ft|m|-2}} below the ground on June 8, 1917, a fire in the Granite Mountain [[shaft mining|shaft]] spewed flames, smoke, and poisonous gas through the labyrinth of tunnels including the connected Speculator Mine.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=Mother Earth |title=Kaiserism in the Copper Industry |author=Carney, Jack |volume=12 |issue=6 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EdBCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA222 |date=August 1917}}</ref> A rescue effort commenced, but [[carbon monoxide]] was contaminating the air supply.<ref name=nogreater>{{cite web|work=Great Falls Tribune|location=Great Falls, Montan|url=https://www.greatfallstribune.com/story/life/my-montana/2017/05/26/no-greater-love-heroes-emerged-buttes-darkest-hours/342796001/|title='No greater love': Heroes emerged in Butte's darkest hours|date=May 26, 2017|author=Inbody, Kristen|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=lm>{{cite web|work=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/20/books/bk-macdonald20|author=Mac Donald, Laura|title=A mine disaster and its ripple effects|date=August 20, 2006|accessdate=May 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025094421/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/20/books/bk-macdonald20|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}} {{closed access}}</ref> Several men barricaded themselves against [[bulkhead (barrier)|bulkheads]] to save their lives, but many others died in a panic to try to escape.<ref name=lm/> Rescue workers set up a fan to prevent the fire from spreading. This worked for a short time, but when the rescuers tried to use water, the water evaporated, creating [[steam]] that burned those trying to escape.{{sfn|Punke|2006|p=54}} Once the fire had been extinguished, recovery of the deceased began; many of the bodies, however, were mutilated beyond recognition, leaving many unidentified.{{sfn|Punke|2006|p=59}} The disaster claimed a total of 168 lives.{{sfn|Punke|2006|p=280}} As of 2017, the event remained the largest hard rock mining accident in history.<ref>{{cite web|work=U.S. News & World Report|publisher=Associated Press|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/montana/articles/2017-06-08/butte-residents-mark-centennial-of-speculator-mine-disaster|date=June 8, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017|title=Butte Residents Mark Centennial of Speculator Mine Disaster|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029121027/https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/montana/articles/2017-06-08/butte-residents-mark-centennial-of-speculator-mine-disaster|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Granite Mountain Memorial in Butte commemorates those who died in the accident.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Missoulian|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/hundreds-attend-granite-mountain-memorial-service/collection_ac349a56-a831-5471-95e6-73f8253e5bb8.html|title=Hundreds attend Granite Mountain memorial service|date=June 9, 2017|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428094158/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/hundreds-attend-granite-mountain-memorial-service/collection_ac349a56-a831-5471-95e6-73f8253e5bb8.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nProtests and strikes were initiated after the Speculator Mine disaster, as well as the establishment of the Metal Mine Workers Union; approximately 15,000 workers abandoned their jobs in the wake of the disaster.{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}} Between 1914 and 1920, the [[National Guard of the United States|U.S. National Guard]] occupied Butte a total of six times to restore civility.{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}} In 1917, copper production from the Butte mines peaked and steadily declined thereafter. By WWII, copper production from the ACM's holdings in Chuquicamata, Chile, far exceeded Butte's production.{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=34}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Montana, Past and Present: Papers Read at a Clark Library Seminar, April 5, 1975|url=https://archive.org/details/montanapastprese0000powe|url-access=registration|author1=Powell, Peter J.|author2=Malone, Michael P.|pages=[https://archive.org/details/montanapastprese0000powe/page/65 65\u20137]|publisher=William Andrews Clark Memorial Library, [[University of California]]|year=1976|series=William Andrews Clark Memorial Library seminar papers|asin=B0006CX6KS}}</ref>\n\n=== Open-pit mining era===\n{{Main|#Berkeley Pit}}\n[[File:The Phantom Foe (1920) - American Theater, Butte, Montana.jpg|thumb|right|Patrons at a matinee of ''[[The Phantom Foe]]'' at the American Theater, December 25, 1920]]\n[[File:Butte Montana 1942 LOC 1a35027u.jpg|thumb|left|1942 view of the city]]\nDisputes between miners' unions and companies continued through the 1920s and 1930s in Butte,{{sfn|Malone|Roeder|Lang|1991|p=329}} with several strikes and protests, one of which lasted for ten months in 1921.<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/mining-city-timeline/article_9bf1c3dd-74b9-5e66-b328-488df21d3824.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Mining City timeline|date=October 4, 2014|accessdate=October 28, 2017|series=Butte, America's decades in photographs|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171028215420/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/mining-city-timeline/article_9bf1c3dd-74b9-5e66-b328-488df21d3824.html|archivedate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On New Year's Eve 1922, protestors attempted to detonate the Hibernian Hall on Main Street with [[dynamite]].<ref name=timeline/><ref name=thornton>{{cite web|work=The Billings Gazette|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/butte-at-years-miners-anaconda-copper-again-at-odds-in/article_8627cc5b-29f4-523c-93b5-919c15d33704.html|title=Butte at 150 years: Miners, Anaconda Copper again at odds in the 1920s|date=January 19, 2015|author=Thortnon, Tracy|accessdate=April 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428181100/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/butte-at-years-miners-anaconda-copper-again-at-odds-in/article_8627cc5b-29f4-523c-93b5-919c15d33704.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFurther industrial expansions included the arrival of the first mail plane in the city in 1928, and in 1937, the city's [[streetcar]] system was dismantled and replaced with bus lines.<ref name=timeline/> After the 1920s, the ACM began to reduce its activities in Butte due to the labor-intensivity of underground mining, as well as competition from other mine holdings in South America.{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}} This ultimately led the Anaconda Company to switch its focus in Butte from [[underground mining]] to [[open pit mining]].{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}}\n\nSince the 1950s, five major developments in the city have occurred: the Anaconda's decision to begin open-pit mining in the mid-1950s,{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}} a series of fires in Butte's business district in the 1970s,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Billings Gazette|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/butte-at-fires-prevalent-in-butte-throughout-the-s/article_3ab5b085-02d0-5e27-9ff7-5462b82d3681.html|title=Butte at 150: Fires prevalent in Butte throughout the '70s|author=Thornton, Tracy|date=February 23, 2015|accessdate=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428180630/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/butte-at-fires-prevalent-in-butte-throughout-the-s/article_3ab5b085-02d0-5e27-9ff7-5462b82d3681.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> a debate over whether to relocate the city's historic business district, a new civic leadership, and the end of copper mining in 1983. In response, Butte looked for ways to diversify the economy and provide employment. The legacy of over a century of environmental degradation has, for example, produced some jobs. Environmental cleanup in Butte, designated a Superfund site, has employed hundreds of people.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Shovers, Brian|title=Remaking the Wide-Open Town: Butte at the End of the Twentieth Century|journal=Montana|date=September 1998|volume=48|issue=3|pages=40\u201353}}</ref>\n\nThousands of homes were destroyed in the Meaderville suburb and surrounding areas, McQueen and East Butte, to excavate the [[Berkeley Pit]], which opened in 1954<ref name=timeline/> by [[Anaconda Copper]].{{sfn|Ring|Watson|Schellinger|2013|p=74}} At the time of its opening, the Berkeley Pit was the largest truck-operated open pit copper mine in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|title=CDIF Socioeconomic Analysis, Butte-Silver Bow Baseline Data|p=30|via=Google Books|author=Montana Energy and MHD Research and Development Institute|year=1978|publisher=United States Department of Energy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjgWL0PDfIoC}} {{free access}}</ref> The Berkeley Pit grew with time until it began encroaching on the Columbia Gardens.{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=191}} After the Gardens caught fire and burned to the ground in November 1973, the Continental Pit was excavated on the former park site.{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=192}} In 1977, the [[ARCO]] (Atlantic Richfield Company) company purchased Anaconda, and only three years later started shutting down mines due to lower metal prices.{{sfn|Finn|1998|pages=66\u20137}} In 1983,{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=67}} all mining in the Berkeley Pit was suspended. The same year, an organization of low income and unemployed residents of Butte formed to fight for jobs and environmental justice; the Butte Community Union produced a detailed plan for community revitalization and won substantial benefits, including a [[Montana Supreme Court]] victory striking down as unconstitutional State elimination of welfare benefits.<ref>McCarthy, Bob J., Re-Claiming Butte: The Doctrine of Subjacent Support, 49 Mont. L. Rev. 267 (1988)</ref> After mining ceased at the Berkeley Pit, water pumps in nearby mines were also shut down, which resulted in highly acidic water laced with toxic heavy metals filling up the pit.<ref name=bp/>\n\n[[File:Berkeley pit1984.jpg|thumb|right|The Berkeley Pit in 1984]]\nAnaconda ceased mining at the Continental Pit in 1983. [[Montana Resources LLP]] bought the property and reopened the Continental Pit in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/05/us/butte-copper-pit-reopens-with-nonunion-miners.html|title=Butte Copper Pit Reopens, with Nonunion Miners|accessdate=April 28, 2018|date=August 5, 1986|author=Robbins, Jim|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428094028/https://www.nytimes.com/1986/08/05/us/butte-copper-pit-reopens-with-nonunion-miners.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}} {{closed access}}</ref> The company ceased mining in 2000, but resumed in the fall of 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/595076167/Mine-reopening-lifts-battered-Butte.html|title=Mine reopening lifts battered Butte|work=The Deseret News|date=July 11, 2004|accessdate=April 28, 2018|last=Gallagher|first=Susan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429091946/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/595076167/Mine-reopening-lifts-battered-Butte.html|archive-date=April 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1880 through 2005, the mines of the Butte district have produced more than 9.6 million metric tons of copper, 2.1 million metric tons of zinc, 1.6 million metric tons of manganese, 381,000 metric tons of lead, 87,000 metric tons of molybdenum, 715 million troy ounces (22,200 metric tons) of silver, and 2.9 million ounces (90 metric tons) of gold.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Czehura, Steve J. |title=Butte: A World Class Ore Deposit|journal=Mining Engineering|date=September 2006|pages=14\u201319}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\n{{See also|#Environmental concerns}}\nFourteen [[headframe]]s still remain over mine shafts in Butte,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitmt.com/listings/general/landmark/headframes.html|work=Visit Montana|title=Headframes|publisher=Montana Office of Tourism|accessdate=April 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428093739/http://www.visitmt.com/listings/general/landmark/headframes.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the city still contains thousands of historic commercial and residential buildings from the boom times,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/high-stakes-in-the-struggle-for-historic-preservation-in-butte/article_16654a60-96a4-11e3-9dca-001a4bcf887a.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428093757/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/high-stakes-in-the-struggle-for-historic-preservation-in-butte/article_16654a60-96a4-11e3-9dca-001a4bcf887a.html|archivedate=April 28, 2018|title=High stakes in struggle for historic preservation in Butte|date=February 16, 2014|author=Smith, Mike|accessdate=April 28, 2018}}</ref> which, especially in the Uptown section, give it an old-fashioned appearance, with many commercial buildings not fully occupied; according to a 2016 estimate, there were \"hundreds\" of unoccupied buildings in Butte, resulting in the city introducing an ordinance to keep record of owners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/butte-sets-new-ordinance-for-vacant-buildings|work=NBC Montana|title=Butte sets new ordinance for vacant buildings|date=June 21, 2016|accessdate=April 28, 2018|author=Lester, Tiffany|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428093510/http://nbcmontana.com/news/local/butte-sets-new-ordinance-for-vacant-buildings|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Preservation efforts of the city's historic buildings began in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Malone, Patrick|title=Butte: Cultural Treasure in a Mining Town|journal=Montana|date= December 1997|volume=47|issue=4|pages=58\u201367}}</ref> As with many industrial cities, tourism and services, especially health care<ref name=top10>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-s-top-employers/article_aaf7400d-b706-5162-88dd-d93e22fc4df6.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Butte's top 10 employers|accessdate=October 28, 2017|author=Hoffman, Matt|date=January 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107015202/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-s-top-employers/article_aaf7400d-b706-5162-88dd-d93e22fc4df6.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> (Butte's St. James Hospital has Southwest Montana's only major trauma center), are rising as primary employers, as well as industrial-sector private companies.<ref name=top10/> Many areas of the city, especially the areas near the old mines, show signs of urban blight but a recent influx of investors and an aggressive campaign to remedy blight has led to a renewed interest in restoring property in Uptown Butte's historic district,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/restoration-option-for-uptown-butte-s-many-ghost-signs/article_b49e08ba-3c38-11e2-bf43-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Restoration option for Uptown Butte's many ghost signs|author=Davis, Francis|date=December 1, 2012|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107010034/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/restoration-option-for-uptown-butte-s-many-ghost-signs/article_b49e08ba-3c38-11e2-bf43-001a4bcf887a.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> which was expanded in 2006 to include parts of [[Anaconda, Montana|Anaconda]] and is one of the largest [[National Historic Landmark District]]s in the United States with 5,991 contributing properties.<ref name=nrhp>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/505/Historic-Preservation|work=The City and County of Butte-Silver Bow, Montana|title=Historic Preservation|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219182508/http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/505/Historic-Preservation|archivedate=December 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=United States National Park Service|url=https://www.nps.gov/nhl/find/statelists/mt/ButteAnacondaHD.pdf|publisher=United States Department of the Interior|title=Butte-Anaconda Historic District: National Register of Historic Places Registration Form|accessdate=April 28, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801101153/https://www.nps.gov/nhl/find/statelists/mt/ButteAnacondaHD.pdf|archivedate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA century after the era of intensive mining and smelting, environmental issues remain in areas around the city. [[Arsenic]] and heavy metals such as [[lead]] are found in high concentrations in some spots affected by old mining, and for a period of time in the 1990s the tap water was unsafe to drink due to poor filtration and decades-old wooden supply pipes. Efforts to improve the water supply have taken place in the past few years, with millions of dollars being invested to upgrade water lines and repair infrastructure. Environmental research and clean-up efforts have contributed to the diversification of the local economy, and signs of vitality, including the introduction of a multimillion-dollar polysilicon manufacturing plant nearby in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Billings Gazette|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/japanese-to-sell-butte-asimi-plant/article_bc9ea0b9-20eb-58c5-85e6-c5806adedea8.html|title=Japanese to sell Butte ASiMI plant|agency=Associated Press|date=February 11, 2005|accessdate=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428094132/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/japanese-to-sell-butte-asimi-plant/article_bc9ea0b9-20eb-58c5-85e6-c5806adedea8.html|archive-date=April 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the late 1990s, Butte was recognized as an [[All-America City Award|All-America City]] and as one of the National Trust for Historic Preservation's Dozen Distinctive Destinations in 2002.<ref name=enc/>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Butte-Silver Bow has a total area of {{convert|1856.55|km2|abbr=on|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|1855.07|km2|mi2|abbr=on|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|1.48|km2|abbr=on|order=flip}} (0.08%) is water.<ref name=censusfacts/> The city is situated on the U.S. [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]].{{sfn|Malone|2006|pages=3\u20134}} Every highway exiting Butte (except westbound I-90) crosses the Divide (eastbound I-90 via Homestake Pass; eastbound MT 2 via Pipestone Pass; northbound I-15 via Elk Park Pass and southbound I-15 via Deer Lodge Pass).{{efn|Refer to map of Butte via [[Google Maps]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Butte,+MT/@45.9050026,-112.9178874,10z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x535a3f36d0ef3cd1:0xb5cd681d4d4f9799!8m2!3d46.0038232!4d-112.5347775|work=Google Maps|title=Butte, Montana|accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>}}\n\nThe city was named for a nearby landform, Big Butte, by the early miners.<ref name=\"mhs\">{{cite web|title=Montana Place Names Companion|url=http://mtplacenames.org/|publisher=Montana Historical Society|accessdate=July 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622083956/http://mtplacenames.org/|archive-date=June 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"names\">{{cite book|last1=Carkeek Cheney|first1=Roberta|title=Names on the Face of Montana|date=1983|publisher=Mountain Press Publishing Company|location=Missoula, Montana|isbn=0-87842-150-5}}</ref> Butte's urban landscape is notable for including mining operations set within residential areas, visible in the form of various headframes throughout the city.<ref>{{cite web|work=Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/more-than-just-history-photos-of-butte-now/collection_c104d16a-a267-5967-8582-18426a881f63.html|title=More than just history: Photos of Butte now|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2018|author=Lewis, Lauren|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423232247/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/more-than-just-history-photos-of-butte-now/collection_c104d16a-a267-5967-8582-18426a881f63.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Geographic location\n|North     = [[Helena, Montana|Helena]]\n|Northwest = [[Deer Lodge, Montana|Deer Lodge]]\n|West      = [[Anaconda, Montana|Anaconda]]\n|Center    = Butte\n|South     = [[Dillon, Montana|Dillon]]\n|East      = [[Bozeman, Montana|Bozeman]]\n|}}\n\n===Cityscapes===\n{{wide image|B.E. view, Butte, Montana LCCN2007662443.tif|850px|View of Butte from south, 1908.}}\n{{wide image|Butte-Panorama 01.jpg|850px|align-cap=center|View from west side, as seen from the [[Montana Tech of the University of Montana|Montana Tech]] campus, 2012.}}\n{{wide image|Panorama from uptown Butte facing south.jpg|850px|align-cap=center|View from uptown Butte facing south on Idaho Street, 2017.}}\n\n===Neighborhoods===\n[[File:Butte uptown.jpg|thumb|right|Uptown Butte, 2006]]\nThe concentration of wealth in Butte due to its mining history resulted in unique and ornate architectural features<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nwtravelmag.com/exploring-historic-butte-montana/|work=Northwest Travel|title=Exploring Historic Butte, Montana|date=May 13, 2015|accessdate=December 28, 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029175710/http://nwtravelmag.com/exploring-historic-butte-montana/|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> amongst its homes and buildings, particularly throughout the uptown section of Butte.<ref name=uptown>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mainstreetbutte.org/homes.htm|work=Main Street Butte|title=Butte's Painted Ladies: A Brief Tour of Butte's West-Side Homes|author=Everett, George|accessdate=October 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061223125835/http://www.mainstreetbutte.org/homes.htm|archivedate=December 23, 2006}}</ref> Uptown, named after its steep streets,<ref name=scandal>{{cite web|work=NBC News|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/46481406/ns/travel-destination_travel/t/huguette-clark-scandal-sparks-interest-copper-king-fathers-lavish-past/#.WfeLqkyZPBI|title=Huguette Clark scandal sparks interest in copper king father's lavish past|author=Geranios, Nicholas K.|publisher=Associated Press|date=February 22, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605064933/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/46481406/ns/travel-destination_travel/t/huguette-clark-scandal-sparks-interest-copper-king-fathers-lavish-past/|archivedate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> is located on a hillside on the northwestern edge of the town and is characterized by its abundance of lavish [[Victorian architecture|Victorian homes]] and [[Queen Anne style architecture in the United States|Queen Anne style]] cottages built in the late-nineteenth century.<ref name=uptown/> Several of Butte's \"[[painted ladies]]\"-homes were featured in the 1987 book ''Daughters of Painted Ladies'' by Elizabeth Pomada.<ref name=uptown/><ref>{{cite book|last=Pomada|first=Elizabeth|title=Daughters of Painted Ladies: America's Resplendent Victorians|year=1987|publisher=Dutton|isbn=978-0-525-24609-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0525246096/page/97 97\u20138]|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0525246096/page/97}}</ref> Butte-Silver Bow County has an established Urban Revitalization Agency which works to improve building fa\u00e7ades to \"enhance and promote the architectural resources of historic uptown Butte.\"<ref name=uptown/> In 2017, a television pilot titled ''Butteification'' aired on [[HGTV]], which focused on a couple restoring a Victorian home in Butte.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/pilot-on-renovated-butte-historic-home-airs-on-hgtv-sunday/article_09f50f9e-2939-527b-a0d8-1f966828cbe4.html|work=Missoulian|publisher=The Montana Standard|title=Pilot on renovated Butte historic home airs on HGTV Sunday, Wednesday|date=June 10, 2017|accessdate=October 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171030042615/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/pilot-on-renovated-butte-historic-home-airs-on-hgtv-sunday/article_09f50f9e-2939-527b-a0d8-1f966828cbe4.html|archive-date=October 30, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nButte's South district, situated at a lower elevation below the hillside that comprises northern Butte, has historically been home to working-class neighborhoods.<ref name=south>{{cite web|url=http://explorebig.org/items/show/39|title=South Butte Neighborhood|work=Explore Big|publisher=Montana Historical Society|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029180859/http://explorebig.org/items/show/39|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Gold mines originally populated south Butte before it was platted for the [[Union Pacific Railroad]] in 1881.<ref name=south/>\n\nThe expansion of the Anaconda Company in the 1960s and 1970s eradicated some of Butte's historic neighborhoods, including the East Side, Dublin Gulch, Meaderville, and [[Chinatown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/special-section/local/lost-neighborhoods/article_4aa17ead-c99b-51ca-bb45-038c19bc1998.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Lost neighborhoods|date=August 21, 2004|accessdate=October 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141024054315/http://mtstandard.com/special-section/local/lost-neighborhoods/article_4aa17ead-c99b-51ca-bb45-038c19bc1998.html|archivedate=October 24, 2014|url-status=dead}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> The St. Mary's section of Butte, which borders uptown to the east, comprised the Dublin Gulch (an enclave for [[Irish people|Irish]] immigrants) and Corktown neighborhoods.<ref name=marys/> It takes its name from the eponymous [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] parish located within it,<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/gathering-of-the-gaels/article_586f433d-a9e8-5d93-ba68-f61fb7af5bd1.html|title=Gathering of the Gaels|accessdate=October 29, 2017|author=Thornton, Tracy|date=September 1, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106081743/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/gathering-of-the-gaels/article_586f433d-a9e8-5d93-ba68-f61fb7af5bd1.html|archivedate=January 6, 2016|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> which was historically known as the \"miner's church,\" scheduling [[Mass (Catholic Church)|masses]] around miners' shifting schedules.<ref name=marys>{{cite web|url=http://explorebig.org/items/show/42|title=St. Mary's Neighborhood|work=Explore Big|publisher=Montana Historical Society|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029181954/http://explorebig.org/items/show/42|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Historically, the St. Mary's section of Butte had a prominent population of [[Slavs|Slavic]] and [[Finns|Finnish]] immigrants in addition to Irish prior to the mid-twentieth century.<ref name=marys/>\n\n===Climate===\nButte has a cold [[semi-arid climate]] (''BSk'') under the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]]. Winters are long and cold, January averaging at {{convert|18|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1|disp=or}}, with 35.9 nights falling below {{convert|0|F|C|1|disp=or}} 58.3 days failing to top freezing.<ref name=\"NOAA\"/> Summers are short, with very warm days and chilly nights: July averages {{convert|63|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|1|disp=or}}. Like most areas in this part of North America, annual precipitation is low and largely concentrated in the spring months: the wettest month since precipitation records began in 1894 has been June 1913 with {{convert|8.86|inch|mm|1|disp=or}}, whilst no precipitation fell in September 1904.<ref name=\"NOW\">[http://w2.weather.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=mso NOW] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904113534/http://w2.weather.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=mso |date=September 4, 2015 }}; [[National Weather Service|NWS]] Forecast Office; Missoula, Montana</ref> The wettest calendar year has been 1909 with {{convert|20.55|inch|mm|1|disp=or}} and the two driest 1935 with {{convert|6.89|inch|mm|1|disp=or}} and 1895 with {{convert|6.98|inch|mm|1|disp=or}}. Snowfall is somewhat limited by dryness: the most in one month being {{convert|32.5|inch|m|2|disp=or}} in October 1911 and the greatest depth on the ground {{convert|27|inch|m|2|disp=or}} on December 28 and 29, 1996.<ref name=\"NOW\"/>\n\nThe coldest month has been January 1937 with a daily mean temperature of {{convert|&minus;5.5|F|C}}, whilst the coldest complete winter was 1948/49 with a three-month mean of {{convert|6.69|F|C}} and the mildest 1925/1926 which averaged {{convert|29.21|F|C}}. July 2007 has been easily the hottest month, with a mean maximum of {{convert|88.8|F|C}}, although the hottest day, reaching {{convert|100|F|C|1|disp=or}}, occurred on July 22, 1931 and June 30, 2000.<ref name=NOAA/>\n{{Weather box \n|location = Butte Mooney Airport, MT (1971-2000; records 1894-2001)\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 58\n|Feb record high F = 61\n|Mar record high F = 69\n|Apr record high F = 83\n|May record high F = 90\n|Jun record high F = 97\n|Jul record high F = 100\n|Aug record high F = 99\n|Sep record high F = 93\n|Oct record high F = 85\n|Nov record high F = 69\n|Dec record high F = 66\n|year record high F = 100\n|Jan high F = 29.7\n|Feb high F = 34.7\n|Mar high F = 42.1\n|Apr high F = 51.6\n|May high F = 60.8\n|Jun high F = 70.7\n|Jul high F = 79.8\n|Aug high F = 79.0\n|Sep high F = 67.0\n|Oct high F = 55.5\n|Nov high F = 38.9\n|Dec high F = 29.9\n|year high F = 53.4\n|Jan low F = 5.4\n|Feb low F = 9.6\n|Mar low F = 18.5\n|Apr low F = 26.4\n|May low F = 34.3\n|Jun low F = 41.4\n|Jul low F = 45.5\n|Aug low F = 44.1\n|Sep low F = 35.3\n|Oct low F = 26.2\n|Nov low F = 15.3\n|Dec low F = 5.7\n|year low F = 25.6\n|Jan record low F = &minus;48\n|Feb record low F = &minus;52\n|Mar record low F = &minus;36\n|Apr record low F = &minus;16\n|May record low F = 9\n|Jun record low F = 22\n|Jul record low F = 28\n|Aug record low F = 23\n|Sep record low F = 3\n|Oct record low F = &minus;23\n|Nov record low F = &minus;42\n|Dec record low F = &minus;52\n|year record low F= &minus;52\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.53\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.47\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.83\n|Apr precipitation inch = 1.02\n|May precipitation inch = 2.02\n|Jun precipitation inch = 2.07\n|Jul precipitation inch = 1.47\n|Aug precipitation inch = 1.36\n|Sep precipitation inch = 1.09\n|Oct precipitation inch = 0.79\n|Nov precipitation inch = 0.60\n|Dec precipitation inch = 0.53\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation days = 7.9\n|Feb precipitation days = 6.0\n|Mar precipitation days = 7.6\n|Apr precipitation days = 8.1\n|May precipitation days = 9.4\n|Jun precipitation days = 9.0\n|Jul precipitation days = 6.1\n|Aug precipitation days = 5.1\n|Sep precipitation days = 6.1\n|Oct precipitation days = 6.7\n|Nov precipitation days = 6.7\n|Dec precipitation days = 7.6\n|unit precipitation days = 0.01 inch\n|Jan snow inch = 8.4\n|Feb snow inch = 7.6\n|Mar snow inch = 10.7\n|Apr snow inch = 8.6\n|May snow inch = 3.3\n|Jun snow inch = 0.2\n|Jul snow inch = 0.0\n|Aug snow inch = 0.3\n|Sep snow inch = 1.1\n|Oct snow inch = 4.5\n|Nov snow inch = 7.4\n|Dec snow inch = 8.3\n|Jan snow days = 7.8\n|Feb snow days = 7.6\n|Mar snow days = 9.6\n|Apr snow days = 6.6\n|May snow days = 2.7\n|Jun snow days = 0.4\n|Jul snow days = 0.0\n|Aug snow days = 0.1\n|Sep snow days = 0.8\n|Oct snow days = 3.2\n|Nov snow days = 7.2\n|Dec snow days = 8.5\n|unit snow days = 0.1 inch\n|source 1 = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|NOAA]]<ref name=\"NOAA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim20/mt/241318.pdf|title=Climatography of the United States No. 20 (1971-2000): BUTTE MOONEY AP, MT|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|accessdate=February 27, 2016|date=February 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114410/http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/climatenormals/clim20/mt/241318.pdf|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 241\n|1880= 3363\n|1890= 10723\n|1900= 30470\n|1910= 39165\n|1920= 41611\n|1930= 39532\n|1940= 37081\n|1950= 33251\n|1960= 27877\n|1970= 23368\n|1980= 37205\n|1990= 33336\n|2000= 33892\n|2010= 33525\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=34284\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529192346/https://census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2016.html|archive-date=May 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|footnote=source:<ref>Moffatt, Riley.  ''Population History of Western U.S. Cities & Towns, 1850\u20131990''. [[Lanham, Maryland|Lanham]]: Scarecrow, 1996, 128.</ref><center>U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=2010census/></center>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2010, there were 33,525 people and 14,628 households residing in Butte-Silver Bow.<ref name=censusfacts>{{cite web|work=[[United States Census Bureau]]|url=https://www.census.gov|title=U.S. Census website|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=2010census>{{cite web|work=United States Census Bureau|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/buttesilverbowbalancemontana/PST045216|title=QuickFacts: Butte-Silver Bow (balance), Montana|accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> The [[population density]] was 46.8 people per square mile (18.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 94.4% [[White (U.S. census)|White]], 0.3% [[African American (U.S. census)|African American]], 1.9% [[Native American (U.S. census)|Native American]], 0.5% [[Asian (U.S. census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. census)|Pacific Islander]], and 2.1% from two or more races.<ref name=censusfacts/> [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race accounted for 3.7% of the population.<ref name=censusfacts/> Of ethnic groups in Butte, the [[Irish Americans|Irish]] make up a significant portion, with over one-quarter of the city's population claiming Irish descent, exceeding the percentage of Irish Americans in [[Boston]].<ref name=irish/> Per capita, Butte has the highest percentage of [[Irish Americans]] of any city in the United States.<ref name=irish/>\n\nThe average household size was 2.22.<ref name=censusfacts/> In the city, the population was spread out with 5.9% under the age of 5, 21.0% under the age of 18, and 16.4% who were 65 years of age or older.<ref name=censusfacts/> 49.5% of residents were female.<ref name=censusfacts/> According to the [[American Community Survey]], from 2012\u20132016, the median income for a household in the city was $39,474.<ref name=2010census/> 19.2% of families were below the [[poverty line]].<ref name=2010census/>\n\nWhile some sources state that Butte had a peak population of nearly 100,000 around 1920, there is no documentation to corroborate this,<ref name=munday>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtech.edu/academics/clsps/ptc/sciencesocietysuperfund/pubs_presentations/butte_mining_history.pdf|publisher=Montana Tech|author=Munday, Pat|date=August 2005|title=Butte Mining, 1864 \u2013 2005: A brief cultural and environmental history|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020210748/http://www.mtech.edu/academics/clsps/ptc/sciencesocietysuperfund/pubs_presentations/butte_mining_history.pdf|archive-date=October 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> though it has been reasoned by local journalists based on [[city directory]] data.{{efn|While the U.S. Census data shows a population of around 60,000 in 1920, a [[city directory]] from 1917 notes Butte's population as being 91,000, while the 1918 directory estimates 93,000. The variance between 1918 and the 1920 census is reflected in the city directories, which fall to 60,000 after 1920.<ref name=gibson>{{cite web|author=Gibson, Richard I.|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/was-butte-s-population-really-during-its-heyday/article_9ce24fa7-bb4e-5661-848a-52fccf142759.html|title=Was Butte's population really 100,000 during its heyday?|date=January 24, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502014817/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/was-butte-s-population-really-during-its-heyday/article_9ce24fa7-bb4e-5661-848a-52fccf142759.html|archivedate=May 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The variance in population reports has been attributed to the city's near-constant fluctuation of visitors, immigrants, and temporary boarders during this time.{{sfn|Everett|2007|p=3}}}}\n\n==Economy==\nAs a mining boomtown, Butte's economy has historically been powered by its copious mining operations which were economical driving forces from the late-nineteenth century into the late-twentieth century. Silver and gold were initially the primary metals mined in Butte, but the abundance of copper in the area would further invigorate the local economy with the advent of electricity, which created a soaring demand for the metal.<ref name=deq/> After [[World War I]], Butte's mining economy experienced a downward trend that continued throughout the twentieth century, until mining operations ceased in 1985 with the closure of the Berkeley Pit.<ref name=deq/> Over the course of its history, the city's mining operations generated over $48 billion worth of ore, making it for a time the richest city in the world.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[CNET|c{{pipe}}net]]|title=How mining nearly killed the 'richest hill on Earth'|author=Terdiman, Daniel|date=July 20, 2009|accessdate=October 31, 2017|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/how-mining-nearly-killed-the-richest-hill-on-earth/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022733/https://www.cnet.com/news/how-mining-nearly-killed-the-richest-hill-on-earth/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMuch of the city's economy post-millennium has been focused in energy companies (such as the [[Renewable Energy Corporation]] and [[NorthWestern Energy]]) and healthcare.<ref name=top10/> In 2014, NorthWestern Energy constructed a $25-million facility in uptown Butte.<ref name=economy>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|author=Hinick, Walter|url=http://mtstandard.com/business/state-of-the-economy-on-the-richest-hill-on-earth/article_3ea72864-3fb7-586b-bff7-f7cb09480741.html|date=June 26, 2016|accessdate=October 29, 2017|title=State of the economy on the 'Richest Hill on Earth'|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818075317/http://mtstandard.com/business/state-of-the-economy-on-the-richest-hill-on-earth/article_3ea72864-3fb7-586b-bff7-f7cb09480741.html|archivedate=August 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe city is served by the Butte Bus system, which operates within Butte as well as to the Montana Tech campus and nearby [[Walkerville, Montana|Walkerville]].<ref>{{cite web|work=The City and County of Butte-Silverbow Montana|title=Transit Services|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323025651/http://co.silverbow.mt.us/178/Transit-Services|url=http://co.silverbow.mt.us/178/Transit-Services|archivedate=March 23, 2017}}</ref> [[Bert Mooney Airport]] has commercial flights on [[Delta Connection]] Airlines and [[Horizon Air]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitmt.com/listings/general/airport/bert-mooney-airport.html|work=Visit Montana|title=Bert Mooney Airport|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001190231/http://www.visitmt.com/listings/general/airport/bert-mooney-airport.html|archivedate=October 1, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nButte can be accessed via [[Interstate 15]] from north\u2013south, and [[Interstate 90]] from east\u2013west; the two intersect in Butte, making Butte and Billings the only cities in Montana situated at a juncture of two interstate highways.  The city can also be accessed from the south via [[Montana Highway 2]] (Old U.S. Route 10).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/507/Getting-Here|work=The City and County of Butte-Silver Bow|title=Getting Here|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110115455/http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/507/Getting-Here|archivedate=January 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUntil 1979 Butte was served by [[Amtrak]]'s [[Chicago]] - [[Seattle]] ''[[North Coast Hiawatha]]'' train. The [[Union Pacific Railroad]] until 1971 ran the ''[[Butte Special]]'' from Butte, south to [[Idaho Falls]], then to [[Salt Lake City]].\n\n== Government ==\n[[File:Mansfield Fed Courthouse.JPG|thumb|right|[[Mike Mansfield Federal Building and United States Courthouse|Mike Mansfield Federal Building and U.S. Courthouse]] in Butte]]\n\n=== Local government ===\nIn 1977, Butte consolidated with [[Silver Bow County, Montana|Silver Bow County]], becoming a [[consolidated city-county]]. It operates under a city-county government. The office of the mayor was eliminated. Mario Micone was the last mayor of Butte. In 1977, Mario became the first Chief Executive of Butte-Silver Bow County.<ref name=facts>{{cite web|work=The City and County of Butte-Silver Bow, Montana|title=Community Factsheet|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130221627/http://co.silverbow.mt.us/377/Community-Factsheet|url=http://co.silverbow.mt.us/377/Community-Factsheet|archivedate=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtgenweb.com/silverbow/mayors_of_butte.htm |title=Mayors of Butte, Montana |publisher=mtgenweb.com |accessdate=July 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720170937/http://www.mtgenweb.com/silverbow/mayors_of_butte.htm |archive-date=July 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nPolitically, Butte has historically been a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] stronghold, owing to its union legacy. Likewise, Silver Bow County has historically been one of the strongest Democratic bastions in Montana.<ref name=bluest>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-the-bluest-of-the-blue/article_4d59a0a7-12b0-5910-bfa7-d6b53a53f981.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Butte: The bluest of the blue|date=September 15, 2014|author=Johnson, Charles S.|accessdate=October 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055118/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-the-bluest-of-the-blue/article_4d59a0a7-12b0-5910-bfa7-d6b53a53f981.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=The New York Times|url=https://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/21/presidential-geography-montana/|title=Presidential Geography: Montana|author=Cohen, Micah|accessdate=October 31, 2017|series=FiveThirtyEight|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708173901/https://fivethirtyeight.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/21/presidential-geography-montana/|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=live}} {{closed access}}</ref> In 1996, Haley Beaudry became the first Republican to represent Butte in the state legislature since 1950.<ref name=bluest/> In 2010, [[Max Yates]] was the next Butte Republican elected to the legislature; however, neither Beaudry or Yates were re-elected.<ref name=bluest/> In 2014, Butte became the third city in Montana to pass an anti-[[discrimination]] ordinance protecting [[LGBT]] residents and visitors from discrimination in employment, housing and public accommodations.<ref>{{cite web|work=Human Rights Campaign|url=https://www.hrc.org/blog/butte-county-commission-passes-non-discrimination-ordinance|title=Montana's Butte County Commission Passes Non-Discrimination Ordinance|date=February 20, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311120611/https://www.hrc.org/blog/butte-county-commission-passes-non-discrimination-ordinance|archive-date=March 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable\n! colspan = 6 | 2016 General Presidential election results of Butte-Silver Bow County (November 8, 2016)<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Montana Presidential Election Results|url=https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/president/montana/|work=[[Politico]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180119220050/https://www.politico.com/2016-election/results/map/president/montana/|archivedate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan = 2 | Candidate party\n! Number of voters\n! Percentage\n|-\n{{party color|Democratic Party (United States)}}\n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] {{small|([[Hillary Clinton]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8,545\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 52.7%\n|-\n{{party color|Republican Party (United States)}}\n| [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] {{small|([[Donald Trump]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6,252\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 38.6%\n|-\n{{party color|Libertarian Party (United States)}}\n| [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] {{small|([[Gary Johnson]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,036\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6.4%\n|-\n{{party color|Green Party (United States)}}\n| [[Green Party (United States)|Green]] {{small|([[Jill Stein]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|289 \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1.8%\n|-\n{{party color|American Delta Party}}\n| [[American Delta Party]] {{small|([[Rocky De La Fuente]])}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 92\n| style=\"text-align:center\"| 0.6%\n|-\n! colspan = 2 | Total\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 16,214\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| 100%\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n===Historical sites and museums===\n[[File:William A. Clark home (Copper King Mansion).jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|[[Copper King Mansion]], built between 1884 and 1888 for magnate [[William A. Clark]]]]\nButte is home to numerous museums and other educational institutions chronicling the city's history. In 2002, Butte was one of only twelve towns in America to be named a Distinctive Destination by the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]].<ref name=enc>{{cite web|work=City of [[Northampton, Massachusetts]]|url=http://archive.northamptonma.gov/WebLink/0/edoc/487297/Dozen%20Distinctive%20Destinations%20-%20National%20Trust%20for%20Historic%20Preservation.pdf|title=Dozen Distinctive Destinations|accessdate=October 30, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20171029192106/http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:http://archive.northamptonma.gov/WebLink/0/edoc/487297/Dozen%2520Distinctive%2520Destinations%2520-%2520National%2520Trust%2520for%2520Historic%2520Preservation.pdf|archive-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Mainstreet Uptown Butte|title=About|url=http://www.mainstreetbutte.org/aboutus.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051231145555/http://www.mainstreetbutte.org/aboutus.htm|archivedate=December 31, 2005|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref> The Butte Silver Bow Public Library, located at 226 W. Broadway in uptown Butte (BSB Library has two branches, one in the mall (South Branch) and a part-time branch in the town of Melrose) is dedicated to preserving the town's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buttepubliclibrary.info|title=Butte Public Library|accessdate=October 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027185107/http://buttepubliclibrary.info/|archive-date=October 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Butte library was created in 1894<!--based on p. 1 of the JSTOR piece--> as \"an antidote to the miners' proclivity for drinking, whoring, and gambling,\" designed to promote middle-class values and to promote an image of Butte as a cultivated city.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Daniel F. |last=Ring |title=The Origins of the Butte Public Library: Some Further Thoughts on Public Library Development in the State of Montana |journal=[[Information & Culture|Libraries & Culture]] |date=1993 |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages=430\u2013444 |jstor=25542594}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |publisher = T.E. Butler |location = Butte |title = Catalogue of Books in the Butte Free Public Library |date = 1894 |ol = 7167999M }}</ref> Additionally, the Butte-Silver Bow Public Archives stores and provides public access to documents and artifacts from Butte's past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsb-mt.us/149/Archives|title=Butte-Silver Bow Public Archives|work=The City and County of Butte-Silver Bow, Montana|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018155120/http://www.bsb-mt.us/149/Archives|archive-date=October 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Digenite--pyrite Leonard Mine, Butte Montana.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|[[Digenite]]-pyrite specimen from the old Leonard Mine, display at MBMG Mineral Museum]]\n\nSeveral museums and attractions are dedicated to the city's mining history, including the MBMG Mineral Museum (located at the [[University of Montana]]'s [[Montana Tech of The University of Montana|Montana Tech]] campus), and the World Museum of Mining located at the Orphan Girl mine in uptown Butte, which features \"Hell Roarin' Gulch,\" a mockup of a frontier mining town.<ref>{{cite web|work=The World History of Mining|title=History|url=http://miningmuseum.org/history/|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161224071017/http://miningmuseum.org/history/|archivedate=December 24, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Berkeley Pit]], a gigantic former open pit copper mine, is also open to the public for viewing.<ref name=bp/> Other museums are dedicated to preserving cultural elements of Butte: The [[Dumas Brothel|Dumas Brothel museum]], a former brothel, is located in [[Venus Alley]], Butte's former historical [[red-light district]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Venus Alley|author=Giecek, Rudy|pages=1\u20135|publisher=Red Light Publishing|year=2005|isbn= 978-0-974-70820-1}}</ref> Another notable site is the Rookwood Speakeasy, a prohibition-era [[speakeasy]] which features an [[underground city]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/ktvm/recovering-history-a-look-inside-buttes-underground_20160509154333294/9173303|work=NBC Montana|title=Recovering history: A look inside Butte's underground|author=Hill, Donovan|date=February 6, 2013|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029193110/http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/ktvm/recovering-history-a-look-inside-buttes-underground_20160509154333294/9173303|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the [[Mai Wah Museum]], dedicated to preserving [[Asian people|Asian]] heritage in the Rocky Mountains.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-in-no-mai-wah-museum/article_577a277d-0e01-5170-9290-7eee2ee3cb54.html|date=August 30, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2017|title=Butte in 75, No. 20: Mai Wah Museum|url-status=live|archivedate=November 7, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022729/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-in-no-mai-wah-museum/article_577a277d-0e01-5170-9290-7eee2ee3cb54.html}}</ref>\n\nThe 34-room [[Copper King Mansion]] in uptown Butte was constructed in 1884 by [[William A. Clark]], one of the city's three [[Copper Kings]].<ref name=scandal/> The mansion functions as a bed-and-breakfast and local museum, and is often reported to be a [[List of reportedly haunted locations in the United States|haunted site]].<ref>{{cite web|work=ABC FOX Montana|url=http://www.abcfoxmontana.com/story/27170202/buttes-haunted-history|title=Butte's Haunted History|accessdate=October 30, 2017|date=October 30, 2014|archivedate=October 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029194335/http://www.abcfoxmontana.com/story/27170202/buttes-haunted-history|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Art Chateau, at one time home to Clark's son, Charles, was designed in the image of a French [[ch\u00e2teau]], and contemporarily houses the Butte-Silver Bow Arts Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/art-chateau-ghost/article_71114c2f-3d41-5204-a054-19915554791c.html|title=Art Chateau Ghost|accessdate=October 30, 2017|date=August 14, 2001|author=Stauffer, Roberta Forsell|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107014503/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/art-chateau-ghost/article_71114c2f-3d41-5204-a054-19915554791c.html|archivedate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLocated above Butte on the northeast edge of the city is the [[Our Lady of the Rockies]] statue, a {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} statue of the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]], dedicated to women and mothers everywhere, situated on top of the [[Continental Divide of the Americas|Continental Divide]].{{sfn|Finn|1998|p=222}} The statue was air-liftedto the site on December 17, 1985, after six years of construction.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/our-lady-of-the-rockies-timeline/article_a7bd8c9e-9541-56b3-998c-ff59896930aa.html|title=Our Lady of the Rockies timeline|accessdate=October 30, 2017|date=December 20, 2015|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029202649/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/our-lady-of-the-rockies-timeline/article_a7bd8c9e-9541-56b3-998c-ff59896930aa.html|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> Butte is also home to the U.S. High Altitude Speed Skating Center, an outdoor speed-skating rink used as a training location for [[ISU Speed Skating World Cup|World Cup]] skaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/ktvm/former-olympic-athletes-reminisce-about-buttes-high-altitude-skating-center-world-cups_20160509194538983/9557940|work=NBC Montana|accessdate=October 29, 2017|title=Former Olympic athletes reminisce about Butte's high-altitude skating center World Cups|date=February 11, 2014|author=Gedeon, Jacqueline|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029201050/http://www.nbcmontana.com/news/ktvm/former-olympic-athletes-reminisce-about-buttes-high-altitude-skating-center-world-cups_20160509194538983/9557940|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThroughout uptown and western Butte are over ten underground mine [[headframe]]s that are remnants from the town's mining industry. These include the Anselmo, the Steward, the Original, the Travona, the Belmont, the Kelly, the Mountain Con, the Lexington, the Bell/Diamond, the Granite Mountain, and the Badger. As part of a community project started around 2004, several headframes were repainted and outlined with [[LED lamp|LED]] lights which are illuminated at night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-in-no-steel-sentinels-headframes-loom-large-as-reminders/article_551da00e-049f-11e4-b0fa-001a4bcf887a.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Butte in 75, No. 75: Steel sentinels: Headframes loom large as reminders, attractions|date=July 6, 2014|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107024833/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-in-no-steel-sentinels-headframes-loom-large-as-reminders/article_551da00e-049f-11e4-b0fa-001a4bcf887a.html|url-status=live|archivedate=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Events and traditions===\n[[File:St Patrick's Day celebration, Butte Montana (2007).jpg|thumb|upright=1|St. Patrick's Day festival in Butte; the city is home to the largest number of [[Irish Americans]] per capita of any city in the United States<ref name=irish/>]]\nButte's longstanding [[Irish Catholics|Irish Catholic]] community (which is the highest per capita of any city in the United States)<ref name=irish>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 12, 2017|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-tr-montana-irish-meagher-20170312-htmlstory.html|title=Celebrate St. Patrick's Day in the most Irish place in the U.S.--and we're not talking about Boston|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Pockock, Joanna|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107022552/http://www.latimes.com/travel/la-tr-montana-irish-meagher-20170312-htmlstory.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}} {{closed access}}</ref> has been celebrated annually on St. Patrick's Day since 1882. Each year, about 30,000 revelers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krtv.com/story/34900092/police-prep-for-potentially-rowdy-st-patricks-day-in-butte|work=KRTV|title=Police prep for potentially rowdy St. Patrick's Day in Butte|author=Emeigh, John|date=March 15, 2017|accessdate=April 30, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316020824/http://www.krtv.com/story/34900092/police-prep-for-potentially-rowdy-st-patricks-day-in-butte|archivedate=March 16, 2017}}</ref> converge on Butte's historic Uptown district to enjoy the parade led by the [[Ancient Order of Hibernians]].<ref name=irish/>\n\nA larger annual celebration is [[Evel Knievel]] Days, held on the last weekend of July, celebrating [[Evel Knievel]] (a Butte native).<ref name=evel>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/friday-evening-and-saturday-s-schedule-for-evel-knievel-days/article_0181cefc-bcfd-537c-9230-07051c4e30c2.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Friday evening, and Saturday's schedule for Evel Knievel Days 2017|date=July 28, 2017|accessdate=October 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729013816/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/friday-evening-and-saturday-s-schedule-for-evel-knievel-days/article_0181cefc-bcfd-537c-9230-07051c4e30c2.html|archivedate=July 29, 2017}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> The weekend-long event, held in Uptown Butte, features various stunt performances, sporting competitions, fundraisers, and live music.<ref name=evel/>\n\nButte is perhaps becoming most renowned for the regional Montana Folk Festival<ref name=historyculture>{{cite web|url=http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/481/History-Culture|work=The City and County of Butte-Silver Bow, Montana|title=History & Culture|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130223252/http://www.co.silverbow.mt.us/481/History-Culture|archivedate=November 30, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> held on the second weekend in July. This event began its run in Butte as the National Folk Festival<ref name=historyculture/> from 2008 to 2010 and in 2011 made the transition to a free-of-admission music festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://montanafolkfestival.com/pages/more/about.php|work=Montana Folk Festival|title=About|accessdate=October 29, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023215100/http://montanafolkfestival.com/pages/more/about.php|archivedate=October 23, 2017}}</ref> Also held in the summer is Butte's [[Independence Day (United States)|Fourth of July]] Parade and Fireworks show.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|title=Shell shocked|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/shell-shocked/article_e44cffc8-f181-51fe-ad6a-82ebe7a2b8ca.html|accessdate=May 1, 2018|date=July 4, 2006|author=Duganz, Pat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502140324/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/shell-shocked/article_e44cffc8-f181-51fe-ad6a-82ebe7a2b8ca.html|archive-date=May 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2008, [[Barack Obama]] spent his last Fourth of July before his Presidency campaigning in Butte, taking in the parade with his family, and celebrating his daughter [[Malia Obama]]'s 10th birthday.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-07-05-2937395846_x.htm|title=Play of the Day: Malia Obama's best birthday|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208232357/https://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-07-05-2937395846_x.htm|archivedate=December 8, 2008|work=USA Today|accessdate=March 20, 2009|last=Loven|first=Jennifer| date=July 5, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe legacy of the immigrants in Butte lives on in the form of various local [[cuisine]], including the [[Pasty|Cornish pasty]] which was popularized by mine workers who needed something easy to eat in the mines, the [[povitica]]\u2014a Slavic nut bread pastry which is a holiday favorite sold in many supermarkets and bakeries in Butte<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|title=Making povitica|url=http://mtstandard.com/special-section/local/making-povitica/article_e6350acf-9f08-577b-81f5-fa060ece6dee.html|author=Silve, Maryanne Davis|accessdate=October 31, 2017|date=December 19, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003751/http://mtstandard.com/special-section/local/making-povitica/article_e6350acf-9f08-577b-81f5-fa060ece6dee.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2014and the boneless porkchop sandwich.<ref name=historyculture/><ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-s-pork-chop-john-dies-at/article_fc64ac53-6682-5978-925c-d29b925dcb1f.html|title=Butte's 'Pork Chop John' dies at 82|date=February 23, 2016|accessdate=October 31, 2017|author=Dunlap, Susan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023928/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-s-pork-chop-john-dies-at/article_fc64ac53-6682-5978-925c-d29b925dcb1f.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental concerns==\n===Berkeley Pit===\n[[File:Berkely Pit, Butte, Montana (45167982).jpg|thumb|left|Because its water contains high concentrations of metals such as copper and zinc, the Berkeley Pit is listed as a federal Superfund site]]\nAfter the closure of the [[Berkeley Pit]] mining operations in 1982, pipes which pumped groundwater out of the pit were turned off, resulting in the pit slowly filling with groundwater, creating an artificial lake.<ref name=bp>{{cite web|work=The Atlantic|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/12/berkeley-pit-geese/510089/|title=The Goose-Killing Lake and the Scientists Who Study It|author=Zhang, Sarah|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029173148/https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2016/12/berkeley-pit-geese/510089/|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Only two years later the pit was classified as a [[Superfund]] site and an environmental hazard site. The water in the pit is contaminated with various hard metals, such as [[arsenic]], [[cadmium]], and [[zinc]].<ref name=bp/>\n\nIt was not until the 1990s that serious efforts to clean up the Berkeley Pit began. The situation gained even more attention after as many as 342 migrating geese chose the pit lake as a resting place, resulting in their deaths.<ref name=bp/> Steps have since been taken to prevent a recurrence, including but not limited to loudspeakers broadcasting sounds to scare off waterfowl. However, in November 2003 the Horseshoe Bend treatment facility went online and began treating and diverting much of the water that would have flowed into the pit.<ref name=kc>{{cite web|work=Billings Gazette|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/some-worry-treatment-plant-won-t-keep-berkeley-pit-water/article_527666b3-a031-5c09-9b25-8a489e86eb04.html|title=Some worry treatment plant won't keep Berkeley Pit water in check|author=Christensen, Kelly|date=November 9, 2014|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029121227/http://billingsgazette.com/news/state-and-regional/montana/some-worry-treatment-plant-won-t-keep-berkeley-pit-water/article_527666b3-a031-5c09-9b25-8a489e86eb04.html|archive-date=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The Berkeley Pit is both a Superfund site and tourist attraction, viewable from an observation deck.<ref name=bp/> Per a 2014 report, scientists believe the Berkeley Pit may reach the critical water level\u2014potentially contaminating Silver Bow Creek\u2014by the year 2023.<ref name=kc/> Beginning in 2019, the Montana Resources and Atlantic Richfield Co. are ordered by the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] to begin treating water from the pit, which is to then be discharged into Silver Bow Creek at a rate of {{convert|7,000,000|USgal|l}} per day.<ref name=kc/> Nikia Greene, EPA project manager for mine flooding, assured in 2014: \"The pit is a giant bathtub. There's a [[hydraulic gradient]] into the pit. We will never let the water reach the critical level.\"<ref name=kc/>\n\n===Upper Clark Fork River===\nThe Upper [[Clark Fork (river)|Clark Fork River]], with Butte at the headwaters, is America's largest Superfund site, spanning {{convert|100|mi|km}}.<ref>{{cite book|title=Paddling Montana: A Guide to the State's Best Rivers|author=Fischer, Kit|pages=42\u20133|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=2015|edition=3rd|isbn=978-1-493-01493-4}}</ref> This area takes in the cities of Butte, [[Anaconda, Montana|Anaconda]], and [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]]. The mining and smelting activity in Butte resulted in significant contamination of the Butte Hill as well as downstream and downwind areas. The contaminated land extends along a corridor of {{convert|120|mi|km|-1}} that reaches to Milltown near Missoula and takes in adjacent areas such as the Anaconda smelter site. Contaminated sediment flooded out from abandoned mines was the root cause of the pollution at the headwaters of the Clark Fork River.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hcn.org/articles/contaminants-montanas-clark-fork-river-superfund-river-cleanup-mercury-pollution-mines|work=High Country News|title=Old mines still plague Montana's Clark Fork|author=McQuillan, Kindra|date=July 10, 2015|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423165957/https://www.hcn.org/articles/contaminants-montanas-clark-fork-river-superfund-river-cleanup-mercury-pollution-mines|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBetween the upstream city of Butte and the downstream city of Missoula lies the Deer Lodge Valley. By the 1970s, local citizens and agency personnel were increasingly concerned over the toxic effects of [[arsenic]] and heavy metals on environment and human health. The Anaconda Copper Mining Corporation (ACM), which merged with the Atlantic Richfield Corporation ([[ARCO]]) in 1977, is considered one of the responsible parties in this contamination.{{sfn|MacMillan|2000|pages=15\u201319}} Shortly thereafter, in 1983, ARCO ceased mining and smelting operations in the Butte-Anaconda area.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of Pollution Control and Waste Minimization|pages=456\u20137|editor=Ghassemi, Abbas|publisher=CRC Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0-203-90793-1}}</ref>\n\nFor more than a century, the Anaconda Copper Mining company mined ore from Butte and smelted it in Butte (prior to {{circa}} 1920) and in nearby Anaconda. During this time, the Anaconda smelter released up to {{convert|40|ST|t|0|lk=on}} per day of arsenic, {{convert|1700|ST|t|-1}} per day of sulfur, and great quantities of lead and other heavy metals into the air.{{sfn|MacMillan|2000|pages=98, 234}} In Butte, mine tailings were dumped directly into Silver Bow Creek, creating a {{convert|150|mi|km}} plume of pollution extending down the valley to Milltown Dam on the Clark Fork River just upstream of Missoula. Air and water borne pollution poisoned livestock and agricultural soils throughout the Deer Lodge Valley. Modern environmental clean-up efforts have continued into the twenty-first century.{{efn|As of 2018, the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) maintains a database entry detailing the Silver Bow Creek/Butte area's pollution and cleanup efforts.<ref>{{cite web|work=Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)|url=https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0800416|title=Superfund Site: Silver Bow Creek/Butte Area|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110124825/https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0800416|archive-date=January 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n==Sports==\nPlaying for the [[Pioneer Baseball League]], the [[Butte Copper Kings]] were first active from 1979\u20131985, then 1987\u20132000; as of 2018, the team is known as the [[Grand Junction Rockies]].<ref>{{cite web|work=NPR|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2011/10/21/141595524/the-casper-ghosts-are-no-more-baseball-team-moves-to-colorado|title=The Casper Ghosts Are No More; Baseball Team Moves To Colorado|date=October 21, 2011|accessdate=April 23, 2018|author=Chappell, Bill|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409044043/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2011/10/21/141595524/the-casper-ghosts-are-no-more-baseball-team-moves-to-colorado|archive-date=April 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHockey teams from Butte have included the [[Butte Irish]] ([[North American Hockey League]]) active from 1996 to 2002, after which they became the [[Wichita Falls Wildcats]];<ref>{{cite web|work=Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/hockey-league-quits-butte/article_4718fd5e-b83e-568a-990e-15839e2bb953.html|title=Hockey league quits Butte|accessdate=April 23, 2018|author=Paisley, Joe|date=May 6, 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170417/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/hockey-league-quits-butte/article_4718fd5e-b83e-568a-990e-15839e2bb953.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Butte Roughriders]] ([[Northern Pacific Hockey League]]), active from 2003 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|work=Missoulian|location=Missoula, Montana|url=http://missoulian.com/sports/maulers/maulers-other-teams-leaving-norpac/article_83367ee2-8d8e-11e0-9519-001cc4c002e0.html|title=Maulers, 3 other teams leaving NorPac|author=Heinbach, Michael|date=June 2, 2011|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170733/http://missoulian.com/sports/maulers/maulers-other-teams-leaving-norpac/article_83367ee2-8d8e-11e0-9519-001cc4c002e0.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The Butte Cobras, a [[Western States Hockey League]] team, was active from 2014 to 2017.<ref>{{cite web|author=Balderas, Al|url=http://mtstandard.com/sports/hockey/butte-cobras-moving-to-na-league-for/article_b3fcbc6f-1259-53b1-97f2-2a664136592a.html|work=The Montana Standard|title=Butte Cobras moving to NA3 League for 2017-18|date=May 30, 2017|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107003931/http://mtstandard.com/sports/hockey/butte-cobras-moving-to-na-league-for/article_b3fcbc6f-1259-53b1-97f2-2a664136592a.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Glacier Nationals franchise in the [[North American 3 Hockey League]] was appointed for the 2017\u201318 season as the Butte Cobras,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://na3hl.com/news/story.cfm?id=21180|work=North American 3 Hockey League|title=Glacier Nationals sold, relocated to Butte, Montana to become Cobras|accessdate=May 1, 2018|date=May 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502140459/http://na3hl.com/news/story.cfm?id=21180|archive-date=May 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> but the team went dormant prior to playing the season.<ref>{{cite web|work=406 MT Sports|url=http://406mtsports.com/hockey/butte-cobras-billings-bulls-go-dormant-week-ahead-of-/article_dc6b9fde-fa2e-59af-b65e-fcfe37d37c13.html|title=Butte Cobras, Billings Bulls go dormant 1 week ahead of 2017-18 season|author=Shockley, Troy|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912223544/http://406mtsports.com/hockey/butte-cobras-billings-bulls-go-dormant-week-ahead-of-/article_dc6b9fde-fa2e-59af-b65e-fcfe37d37c13.html|archive-date=September 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Butte Daredevils]] ([[Continental Basketball Association]]), active from 2006 to 2008, were named for Butte native [[Evel Knievel]].<ref>{{cite web|work=Missoulian|location=Missoula, Montana|url=http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/cba-commissioner-says-butte-daredevils-are-defunctposted-on-aug/article_36c0e596-c372-5968-8086-db057f84601b.html|title=CBA commissioner says Butte Daredevils are defunctPosted on Aug. 15|date=August 15, 2008|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170805/http://missoulian.com/news/state-and-regional/cba-commissioner-says-butte-daredevils-are-defunctposted-on-aug/article_36c0e596-c372-5968-8086-db057f84601b.html|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nUniversity teams include the [[Montana Tech of the University of Montana|Montana Tech]] Orediggers, who have competed in the [[Frontier Conference]] of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] since the league's founding in 1952. The school hosts men's and women's basketball, football, golf, and women's volleyball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.godiggers.com|work=godiggers.com|title=Montana Tech Orediggers|publisher=Montana Tech|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180423170804/http://www.godiggers.com/|archive-date=April 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:MontanaTecGate.jpg|thumb|right|Entrance of Montana Tech. A statue of [[Marcus Daly]] by [[Augustus Saint-Gaudens]] sits at the entrance]]\nPublic education is provided by Butte Public Schools. [[Butte High School (Butte, Montana)|Butte High School]] enrolls around 1,300 students.<ref>{{cite web|work=U.S. News & World Report|title=Butte High School|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/montana/districts/butte-school-district/butte-high-school-12044|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329033440/https://www.usnews.com/education/best-high-schools/montana/districts/butte-school-district/butte-high-school-12044|archivedate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> In correspondence with the Butte Public Schools system, the Butte Education Foundation was established in 2006, which aims to revitalize the public schools in an effort to attract new businesses and residents.<ref name=edfound>{{cite web|work=The Butte Education Foundation|title=History of the Foundation|url=http://butteeducationfoundation.org/History_of_the_foundation.aspx|accessdate=November 3, 2017|archivedate=December 17, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151217185733/http://butteeducationfoundation.org/History_of_the_foundation.aspx}}</ref> In the foundation's mission statement, it is noted that there is a \"need to demonstrate a genuine and ongoing commitment to public education. Schools are often the first thing visitors ask about when looking at Butte as a potential new home.\"<ref name=edfound/>\n\nThere are several private schools in Butte: The [[Butte Central Catholic High School]] operates under the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Helena|Diocese of Helena]],<ref>{{cite web|work=The Roman Catholic Diocese of Helena|title=High Schools|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url=http://diocesehelena.org/education/high-schools/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219034730/http://diocesehelena.org/education/high-schools/|archivedate=December 19, 2014}}</ref> which also operates Butte Central Elementary, a Catholic [[elementary school]].<ref>{{cite web|work=The Roman Catholic Diocese of Helena|title=Elementary Schools|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219035236/http://diocesehelena.org/education/elementary-schools/|url=http://diocesehelena.org/education/elementary-schools/|archivedate=December 19, 2014}}</ref> Other private elementary schools include the Silver Bow [[Montessori school|Montessori School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silverbowmontessori.org|title=Silver Bow Montessori School|work=www.silverbowmontessori.org|accessdate=November 3, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927222742/http://www.silverbowmontessori.org/|archivedate=September 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe first institute of higher education in Butte was the Montana School of Mines, which was established in 1889, the year of Montana's statehood.<ref name=catalog>{{cite web|url=http://archive.umt.edu/catalog/13_14/affiliated/ummontech/default.html|work=University of Montana|title=Montana Tech of The University of Montana|series=2013\u20132014 Course Catalog|accessdate=November 3, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171103211000/http://archive.umt.edu/catalog/13_14/affiliated/ummontech/default.html|archivedate=November 3, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The university changed its name to [[Montana Tech of the University of Montana|Montana Tech]] in the mid-twentieth century, and in 1994 became affiliated with the [[University of Montana]].<ref name=ustech>{{Cite web|work=U.S. News & World Report|title=Montana Tech of the University of Montana|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/montana-tech-2531|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170707010158/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/montana-tech-2531|archivedate=July 7, 2017}}</ref> The university specializes in engineering as well as [[geology|geologic]] and [[hydrogeology|hydrogeologic]] research.<ref name=catalog/> It was ranked no. 4 by the [[U.S. News & World Report]] in 2017 for \"Best Regional Colleges in the West.\"<ref name=ustech/> Montana Tech is also home to Highlands College, a two-year-college that grants associate's and trade degrees.<ref>{{cite web|work=Montana Tech|title=Highlands College|url=http://www.mtech.edu/academics/highlands/|accessdate=November 1, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905211753/http://www.mtech.edu/academics/highlands/|archivedate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\n===Radio and television===\nMajor [[AM broadcasting|AM]] stations in Butte are [[KBOW]] AM 550 (country), [[KANA]] 580 (oldies), and [[KXTL]] 1370 (oldies and [[talk radio]]).<ref name=radio>{{cite web|work=Streaming Radio Guide|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170612005405/http://streamingradioguide.com/radio-station-list-by-state.php?state=MT|archivedate=June 12, 2017|url=http://streamingradioguide.com/radio-station-list-by-state.php?state=MT|title=Radio and TV Stations in Montana|accessdate=October 30, 2017}} {{small|(Link requires scroll down).}}</ref> [[FM broadcasting|FM]] stations include [[KAPC]] 91.3 [[Montana Public Radio]] (via the [[University of Montana]]); [[KAAR]] 92.5 (country); [[KOPR]] 94.1 (classic rock), [[KMBR]] 95.5 (mainstream rock), [[KQRV]] 96.9 (country), [[KGLM]] 97.7 (contemporary), [[KMSM]] 103.9 ([[Variety (US radio)|variety]]), and KBMF 102.5 [[community radio]] ([[classical music|classical]]; via [[Montana State University]]).<ref name=radio/>\n\nButte shares its [[Nielsen Media Research|Neilsen]] market with nearby [[Bozeman, Montana|Bozeman]], with which it forms the 194th largest TV market in the United States. Local television stations include: [[KXLF]] (Channel 4), a [[CBS]]/[[The CW Television Network|CW]] affiliate, and the oldest broadcast television station in the state of Montana; [[KTVM]] (Channel 6), an [[NBC]] affiliate with additional programming from nearby [[KECI-TV]] in [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]]; [[KUSM]] (Channel 9), a [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] affiliate broadcasting out of [[Montana State University - Bozeman|Montana State University]] in Bozeman; and [[KWYB]] (Channel 19), an [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]/[[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] affiliate and last of the \"Big Three\" networks to come into the market (1992). Prior to this Butte's ABC feeds came from [[KUSA-TV]] in [[Denver, Colorado]] and FOX from now-defunct Butte station [[KBTZ]].<ref>{{cite book|p=254|title=Censored 2007: The Top 25 Censored Stories|editor=Phillips, Peter|year=2011|publisher=Seven Stories Press|isbn=978-1-583-22976-7}}</ref>\n\n===Newspapers===\nButte has one local daily, a weekly paper, as well as several papers from around the state of Montana. ''[[The Montana Standard]]'' is Butte's daily paper. It was founded in 1928 and is the result of ''The Butte Miner'' and the ''[[Anaconda, Montana|Anaconda]] Standard'' merging into one daily paper.<ref name=loc>{{cite web|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84024813/|title=About The Montana standard. (Butte, Mont.) 1928-1961|work=[[Library of Congress]]|series=Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers|accessdate=October 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220213815/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84024813/|archive-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Standard'' is owned by [[Lee Enterprises]]. ''The Butte Weekly'' is another local paper.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/business/butte-weekly-to-begin-new-year-with-new-owner/article_3cd45be2-1401-558d-9747-99d5feecb60f.html|title=Butte Weekly to begin New Year with new owner|author=Pentilla, Annie|date=December 29, 2016|accessdate=April 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425115208/http://mtstandard.com/business/butte-weekly-to-begin-new-year-with-new-owner/article_3cd45be2-1401-558d-9747-99d5feecb60f.html|archive-date=April 25, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n===Film and television===\nButte has appeared in numerous films. The first film to notably feature Butte was ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'' (1971), a [[biopic]] of [[Evel Knievel]], a Butte native.<ref>{{cite book|author=Montville, Leigh|page=5|title=Evel: The High-Flying Life of Evel Knievel: American Showman, Daredevil, and Legend|publisher=Knopf Doubleday|isbn=978-0-767-93052-9|year=2012}}</ref> The 1976 thriller ''[[The Killer Inside Me (1976 film)|The Killer Inside Me]]'', starring [[Stacy Keach]] and [[Susan Tyrrell]] and set in small-town Montana, was also partially shot in Butte in September 1974.<ref>{{cite news|work=The Montana Standard|title=Fire sends actors scurrying|date=September 12, 1974|page=13}}</ref> The city was featured in the [[period piece]]s ''[[Runaway Train (film)|Runaway Train]]'' (1985), which was shot in-part on the [[Butte, Anaconda and Pacific Railway]],<ref>{{cite web|work=AlaskaRails.org|title=Runaway Train|url=http://www.alaskarails.org/sf/film/runaway-train/|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041213182654/http://www.alaskarails.org/sf/film/runaway-train/|archivedate=December 13, 2004}}</ref> and the miniseries ''[[Return to Lonesome Dove]]'' (1993).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/western-movies-turn-montana-takes-star-turn-in-film/article_bb4dcd26-cd71-5ca5-8fee-6304bc5045ea.html|author=Meyers, Christene|date=September 20, 2003|accessdate=December 28, 2016|title=Western movies turn 100: Montana takes star turn in film|work=Billings Gazette|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107004612/http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/western-movies-turn-montana-takes-star-turn-in-film/article_bb4dcd26-cd71-5ca5-8fee-6304bc5045ea.html|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Other films shot in Butte include ''[[F.T.W. (film)|F.T.W.]]'' (1994),<ref>{{cite web|work=Film in America|title=The Last Ride|url=http://www.filminamerica.com/Movies/TheLastRide/|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archivedate=December 25, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225014143/http://www.filminamerica.com/Movies/TheLastRide/}}</ref>\n\nThe animated film ''[[Beavis and Butt-head Do America]]'' (1996) depicts Butte.<ref>{{cite web|work=Billings Gazette|url=http://billingsgazette.com/entertainment/movies/when-in-beavis-and-butthead-do-america-beavis-and-butthead/youtube_1a82b8ae-414b-5662-9f1d-33956a4c724f.html|title=When, in \"Beavis and Butthead Do America,\" Beavis and Butthead travel through Butte and call it \"Butt\"|date=February 9, 2015|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171030200940/http://billingsgazette.com/news/features/magazine/western-movies-turn-montana-takes-star-turn-in-film/article_bb4dcd26-cd71-5ca5-8fee-6304bc5045ea.html|archivedate=October 30, 2017|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> In 2004, the [[Wim Wenders]] film ''[[Don't Come Knocking]]'' was set and shot in Butte.<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/former-butte-girls-in-l-a-review-don-t-come/article_b35bb595-e603-5199-a0e9-0e535b11991c.html|title=Former Butte girls in L.A. review 'Don't Come Knocking'|date=March 24, 2006|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150920212901/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/former-butte-girls-in-l-a-review-don-t-come/article_b35bb595-e603-5199-a0e9-0e535b11991c.html|archivedate=September 20, 2015|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref> In 2015, the [[SyFy]]-produced horror film ''[[Dead 7]]'' was shot at the city's Anselmo Mine yards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/dead-on-location/image_1fc08ccb-919c-5ae6-923e-3173df2703e1.html|work=The Montana Standard|title='Dead 7' on location|date=August 22, 2015|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Hinick, Walter|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829163610/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/dead-on-location/image_1fc08ccb-919c-5ae6-923e-3173df2703e1.html|url-status=live|archivedate=August 29, 2015}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref>\n\nThe city has been subject of several documentary films, including ''Die Vergessene Stadt: Butte, Montana'' (1992), a German documentary by Thomas Schadt,<ref>{{cite web|work=Big Sky Documentary Film Festival|url=http://www.bigskyfilmfest.org/archives/archived_films-2015/die_vergessene_stadt_butte_montana/2014|title=Die Vergessene Stadt: Butte, Montana|accessdate=December 20, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420044354/http://www.bigskyfilmfest.org/archives/archived_films-2015/die_vergessene_stadt_butte_montana/2014|archivedate=April 20, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and ''[[Butte, America]]'' (2008), narrated by [[Gabriel Byrne]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/independentlens/butte-america/|work=PBS|title=Butte, America|series=Independent Lens|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223222945/http://www.pbs.org/independentlens/butte-america//|archivedate=December 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Literary depictions===\nOne of the earliest literary depictions of Butte was by [[Mary MacLane]], a diarist who wrote of her life growing up in the town at the turn of the twentieth century. Her diaries are published under the title ''I Await the Devil's Coming'', and have been credited as a progenitor of [[confessional writing]].<ref>{{cite web|work=The Atlantic|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/sexes/archive/2013/03/the-forgotten-story-of-mary-maclane-1902s-racy-angsty-teenage-diarist/274149/|title=The Forgotten Story of Mary MacLane, 1902's Racy, Angsty Teenage Diarist|date=March 19, 2013|author=Reese, Hope|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107011433/https://www.theatlantic.com/sexes/archive/2013/03/the-forgotten-story-of-mary-maclane-1902s-racy-angsty-teenage-diarist/274149/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The city also figures in the noir novel ''[[Red Harvest]]'' by [[Dashiell Hammett]], which is set in Butte and whose plot is partly based on the 1920 [[Anaconda Road Massacre]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Red Harvest and Dashiell Hammett's Butte|publisher=Montana Tech at the University of Montana|author=Crowley, Jack|journal=The Montana Professor|date=2008|volume=18|number=2|url=http://mtprof.msun.edu/Spr2008/crowl.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501123915/http://mtprof.msun.edu/spr2008/crowl.html|archivedate=May 1, 2016}}</ref> The 1980 novel ''The Butte Polka'' by [[Donald McCaig]] also incorporates the city's mining history into its plot, featuring a character who goes missing from his post at a Butte copper mine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/donald-mccaig-2/the-butte-polka/|work=Kirkus Reviews|title=The Butte Polka by Donald McCaig|accessdate=October 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107040312/https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/donald-mccaig-2/the-butte-polka/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMore contemporary literary depictions of Butte can be found in 1998's ''Buster Midnight's Cafe'' by Sandra Dallas,<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|url=http://ew.com/article/1990/05/04/buster-midnights-cafe/|title=Buster Midnight's Cafe|date=May 4, 1990|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Hodgman, George|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013250/http://ew.com/article/1990/05/04/buster-midnights-cafe/|archive-date=November 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as the [[historical fiction]] novel ''Go By Go'' by Jon A. Jackson, which depicts the 1917 [[Speculator Mine disaster]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Go by Go|author=Jackson, Jon A.|publisher=Dennis McMillan Publications|year=1998|isbn= 978-0-939-76731-1|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Go_by_Go.html?id=dKLJuPip4OMC}}</ref> [[Ivan Doig]]'s 2010 novel ''Work Song'' and his 2013 novel ''Sweet Thunder'' are set in Butte in 1919 and 1920 respecively, after World War I.<ref>{{cite web|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Book review: 'Work Song' by Ivan Doig|date=July 15, 2010|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Rutten, Tim|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/entertainment/la-et-rutten-20100714|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529095004/http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/15/entertainment/la-et-rutten-20100714|archive-date=May 29, 2016|url-status=live}} {{closed access}}</ref>\n''Confessions of a Shanty Irishman'' by Michael Corrigan has a chapter-story set in Butte during the Speculator mining disaster and riots.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Butte, Montana}}\n\n==Sister cities==\n*{{flagdeco|Germany}} [[Altensteig]], [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]], Germany {{small|(since 1991)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/a-cultural-experience-german-students-attend-butte-high-in-exchange/article_ab3bc0a6-e54a-11df-9b53-001cc4c002e0.html|author=Gevock, Nick|work=The Montana Standard|date=November 1, 2010|accessdate=December 26, 2016|title=A cultural experience: German students attend Butte High in exchange program|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029183708/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/a-cultural-experience-german-students-attend-butte-high-in-exchange/article_ab3bc0a6-e54a-11df-9b53-001cc4c002e0.html|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref>\n*{{flagdeco|Poland}} [[Bytom]], [[Silesian Voivodeship]], Poland {{small|(since 2001)}}<ref>{{cite web|work=The Montana Standard|url=http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-officials-off-to-poland-to-meet-sister-city/article_01c3a601-14e0-5189-901f-8ffdd37846eb.html|date=May 18, 2001|accessdate=October 29, 2017|author=Stauffer, Roberta Forsell|title=Butte officials off to Poland to meet sister city|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20171029184155/http://mtstandard.com/news/local/butte-officials-off-to-poland-to-meet-sister-city/article_01c3a601-14e0-5189-901f-8ffdd37846eb.html|archivedate=October 29, 2017|url-status=live}} {{small|(Archive link requires scroll down).}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Anaconda Copper Mine (Montana)]]